  "answer": "Both scenes stage an interrogation across an ontological gap, but the quality of interrogation differs markedly.\n\n**Juliana** (cynewulf-juliana-9a2157, ch. 1): The representative moment is the sustained cross-examination Juliana conducts after physically seizing the demon who came disguised as an angel. God commands her to hold him fast until he tells her 'his whole journey from the beginning' (p-28b423). She then drives the interrogation over multiple rounds:\n\n— Round 1 (p-bd327c): 'You must tell me further, fiend of mankind, of your journey, and who sent you to me.' The demon capitulates, identifying his father as 'the king of hell's inhabitants.'\n— Round 2 (p-def3ab): 'Then the holy one began again to question the enemy of heroes... You must tell me further, fiend of souls, how you most harm the righteous through the slide of sin.' The demon then delivers a detailed confession of his psychological tactics.\n— Round 3 (p-d3a506): Juliana demands still more: 'You must confess more of your evil deeds, lowly hell-spirit, before you may go from here.' The demon admits he is compelled by force to reveal his mind.\n\nJuliana controls the pace, the topic, and the depth of disclosure. She extracts a comprehensive taxonomy of demonic method — from the blinding of eyes to the kindling of lust, from the corruption of prayer to the engineering of blood feuds. The demon, at the end, confesses she has bested every human he has ever faced: 'There was none who so boldly bound me in chains, crushed me with force, until you now have overcome my great might' (p-15a5a2/p-6b7e11).\n\n**Andreas** (cynewulf-andreas-07b573, ch. 1): The representative moment is Andreas's confrontation with the devil who directs the Mermedonians and then visits him in prison. When the devil appears before the Mermedonian host and names Andreas as the enemy to kill, Andreas retorts (p-51b3f4): 'Behold, you boldly instruct this people, you urge them to battle! You know the bale-fire's torment, hot in hell, yet you incite this host... See, you devil's-dart, you increase your own anguish. The Almighty humbled you, the high one, and into darkness shoved you.' Later, in the prison cell, the demon poses a rhetorical challenge: 'Who is so mighty over middle-earth, that he can release you from your limb-bonds, of all mankind, against my will?' (p-1d292e). Andreas answers (p-ca8f6e): 'Behold, the Almighty God can easily save me... There you ever since, bound in torment, have dwelled in exile... You shall for all time extend your anguish.'\n\nAndreas's mode is declaration, not interrogation — he does not extract information; he asserts theological facts and refuses to be moved. He is effective as a confessor and a defiant witness, but he never reverses the ontological power dynamic: the demon asks, he answers.\n\n**Who is the more skilled interrogator?** Juliana, unambiguously. She is the only one of the two who actually interrogates: she holds the subject, sets the agenda, demands successive layers of disclosure, and extracts a confession so complete that the demon himself credits her as uniquely powerful over all humanity. Andreas's confrontations with the demonic forces behind the Mermedonians are impressive as acts of witness and endurance, but they are reactive and declarative rather than inquisitorial. The ontological gap in Juliana's scene closes from below — a captive human mortal makes a supernatural being answer to her. In Andreas's scene, the gap is never closed; it is merely endured.",
